# View (Base UI Object)

`Dali::Ui::View` is the base app-facing UI component handle for building, styling, measuring, animating, and interacting with dali-ui views.

## Table of Contents

- [Creating and Keeping View Handles](#creating-and-keeping-view-handles)
- [Working with View Trees](#working-with-view-trees)
- [Reading Layout and Visual State](#reading-layout-and-visual-state)
- [Making a View Interactive](#making-a-view-interactive)
- [Adding Selection State](#adding-selection-state)
- [Animating a View](#animating-a-view)
- [Using View Property Identifiers](#using-view-property-identifiers)

## Creating and Keeping View Handles

Use `Dali::Ui::View::New()` to create a base view. A `Dali::Ui::View` handle can be copied or stored; copied handles refer to the same underlying view object.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

using namespace Dali;
using namespace Dali::Ui;

class PanelController : public ConnectionTracker
{
public:
  void Create()
  {
    mPanel = View::New();

    UiColor initialColor = mPanel.GetBackgroundColor();
    UiColor currentColor = mPanel.GetCurrentColor();

    (void)initialColor;
    (void)currentColor;
  }

private:
  View mPanel;
};
```

`Dali::Ui::View` is the dali-ui app-facing object model for UI component handles. Use it for application code that needs a UI object handle, and reserve lower-level DALi object concepts for framework setup or integration code.

## Working with View Trees

A view can contain child views. For app-level traversal, use `Dali::Ui::View::GetChildCount()` and `Dali::Ui::View::GetChildAt()` so your code stays in the view object model.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

using namespace Dali;
using namespace Dali::Ui;

void VisitDirectChildren(View container)
{
  const uint32_t childCount = container.GetChildCount();

  for(uint32_t index = 0u; index < childCount; ++index)
  {
    View child = container.GetChildAt(index);

    UiColor childColor = child.GetColor();
    MeasuredSize childSize = child.GetCurrentSize();

    (void)childColor;
    (void)childSize;
  }
}
```

`Dali::Ui::View::GetChildAt()` returns a `Dali::Ui::View`, so follow-up code can continue to use view APIs such as `Dali::Ui::View::GetName()`, `Dali::Ui::View::GetCurrentPosition()`, and `Dali::Ui::View::GetEffectiveLayoutDirection()`.

```cpp
void InspectFirstChild(View container)
{
  if(container.GetChildCount() == 0u)
  {
    return;
  }

  View firstChild = container.GetChildAt(0u);

  Dali::String name = firstChild.GetName();
  Vector2 position = firstChild.GetCurrentPosition();
  Dali::LayoutDirection::Type direction = firstChild.GetEffectiveLayoutDirection();

  (void)name;
  (void)position;
  (void)direction;
}
```

## Reading Layout and Visual State

`Dali::Ui::View` exposes layout results and visual styling through typed getters. Use these getters when you need to inspect the state produced by layout, styling, or animation.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

using namespace Dali;
using namespace Dali::Ui;

struct ViewSnapshot
{
  MeasuredSize currentSize;
  Vector2 currentPosition;
  Vector2 currentScale;
  UiColor backgroundColor;
  UiColor color;
  Extents margin;
};

ViewSnapshot CaptureViewSnapshot(View view)
{
  ViewSnapshot snapshot;
  snapshot.currentSize = view.GetCurrentSize();
  snapshot.currentPosition = view.GetCurrentPosition();
  snapshot.currentScale = view.GetCurrentScale();
  snapshot.backgroundColor = view.GetBackgroundColor();
  snapshot.color = view.GetColor();
  snapshot.margin = view.GetMargin();
  return snapshot;
}
```

For corner and borderline state, use `Dali::Ui::View::GetCornerRadius()`, `Dali::Ui::View::GetCornerRadiusPolicy()`, `Dali::Ui::View::GetCornerSquareness()`, `Dali::Ui::View::GetBorderlineWidth()`, `Dali::Ui::View::GetBorderlineColor()`, and `Dali::Ui::View::GetBorderlineOffset()`.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

using namespace Dali;
using namespace Dali::Ui;

bool HasVisibleOutline(View view)
{
  const float width = view.GetBorderlineWidth();
  const UiColor color = view.GetBorderlineColor();
  const float offset = view.GetBorderlineOffset();

  Vector4 radius = view.GetCornerRadius();
  Vector4 squareness = view.GetCornerSquareness();
  CornerRadiusPolicy policy = view.GetCornerRadiusPolicy();

  (void)color;
  (void)offset;
  (void)radius;
  (void)squareness;
  (void)policy;

  return width > 0.0f;
}
```

## Making a View Interactive

Use the interactive trait when a view should respond to input. The preferred dali-ui pattern is to obtain `Dali::Ui::InteractiveTrait` from the view with `Dali::Ui::View::AsInteractive()` and connect handlers on the trait.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

using namespace Dali;
using namespace Dali::Ui;

class ButtonController : public ConnectionTracker
{
public:
  void Configure(View button)
  {
    button.AsInteractive([this](InteractiveTrait& trait)
    {
      trait.SetClickable(true);
      trait.ConnectClickedSignal(this, &ButtonController::OnClicked);
      trait.ConnectPressedChangedSignal(this, &ButtonController::OnPressedChanged);
      trait.ConnectLongPressedSignal(this, &ButtonController::OnLongPressed);
    });
  }

private:
  void OnClicked(View view, InputEvent event)
  {
    UiColor currentColor = view.GetCurrentColor();

    (void)event;
    (void)currentColor;
  }

  void OnPressedChanged(View view, bool pressed, InputEvent event)
  {
    bool isPressed = pressed;

    (void)view;
    (void)event;
    (void)isPressed;
  }

  bool OnLongPressed(View view, InputEvent event)
  {
    (void)view;
    (void)event;

    return true;
  }
};
```

`Dali::Ui::InteractiveTrait::ClickedSignal()` emits `void(View, InputEvent)`. `Dali::Ui::InteractiveTrait::PressedChangedSignal()` emits `void(View, bool, InputEvent)`. `Dali::Ui::InteractiveTrait::LongPressedSignal()` emits `bool(View, InputEvent)`, where returning `true` suppresses the subsequent click.

```cpp
void ConfigureInputPolicy(View view)
{
  view.AsInteractive([](InteractiveTrait& trait)
  {
    trait.SetKeyClickPolicy(KeyClickPolicy::ON_RELEASE);

    const bool clickable = trait.IsClickable();
    const bool pressed = trait.IsPressed();
    const bool pseudoDisabled = trait.IsPseudoDisabled();
    const KeyClickPolicy policy = trait.GetKeyClickPolicy();

    (void)clickable;
    (void)pressed;
    (void)pseudoDisabled;
    (void)policy;
  });
}
```

Use `Dali::Ui::InteractiveTrait::SetPseudoDisabled()` when a view should present a disabled-like state while still receiving input for guidance or an alternate flow.

```cpp
class PseudoDisabledController : public ConnectionTracker
{
public:
  void Configure(View view)
  {
    view.AsInteractive([this](InteractiveTrait& trait)
    {
      trait.SetPseudoDisabled(true);
      trait.PseudoDisabledChangedSignal().Connect(
        this,
        &PseudoDisabledController::OnPseudoDisabledChanged);
    });
  }

private:
  void OnPseudoDisabledChanged(View view, bool pseudoDisabled)
  {
    (void)view;
    (void)pseudoDisabled;
  }
};
```

## Adding Selection State

Use `Dali::Ui::SelectableTrait` when a view needs a selected state. Selection can be changed directly with `Dali::Ui::SelectableTrait::SetSelected()` or toggled by click with `Dali::Ui::SelectableTrait::EnableToggleByClick()`.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

using namespace Dali;
using namespace Dali::Ui;

class SelectionController : public ConnectionTracker
{
public:
  void Configure(View item)
  {
    item.AsSelectable([this](SelectableTrait& trait)
    {
      trait.EnableToggleByClick(true);
      trait.SelectionChangedSignal().Connect(
        this,
        &SelectionController::OnSelectionChanged);
    });
  }

private:
  void OnSelectionChanged(View view, bool selected, InputEvent event)
  {
    UiColor currentColor = view.GetCurrentColor();

    (void)selected;
    (void)event;
    (void)currentColor;
  }
};
```

`Dali::Ui::SelectableTrait::SelectionChangedSignal()` emits `void(View, bool, InputEvent)`. The `bool` argument is the new selected state.

```cpp
void SelectProgrammatically(View item)
{
  item.AsSelectable([](SelectableTrait& trait)
  {
    trait.SetSelected(true);

    const bool selected = trait.IsSelected();
    const bool togglesByClick = trait.IsToggleByClickEnabled();

    (void)selected;
    (void)togglesByClick;
  });
}
```

`Dali::Ui::SelectableTrait` can coexist with `Dali::Ui::InteractiveTrait` on the same `Dali::Ui::View`, so a selectable item can still handle click, press, or long-press behavior.

```cpp
class SelectableButtonController : public ConnectionTracker
{
public:
  void Configure(View item)
  {
    item.AsInteractive([this](InteractiveTrait& trait)
    {
      trait.ConnectClickedSignal(this, &SelectableButtonController::OnClicked);
    });

    item.AsSelectable([this](SelectableTrait& trait)
    {
      trait.EnableToggleByClick(true);
      trait.SelectionChangedSignal().Connect(
        this,
        &SelectableButtonController::OnSelectionChanged);
    });
  }

private:
  void OnClicked(View view, InputEvent event)
  {
    (void)view;
    (void)event;
  }

  void OnSelectionChanged(View view, bool selected, InputEvent event)
  {
    (void)view;
    (void)selected;
    (void)event;
  }
};
```

## Animating a View

Use `Dali::Ui::View::Animate()` for a one-off animation on a specific view. The view remains the app-facing object being animated.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

using namespace Dali;
using namespace Dali::Ui;

void FadeAndMove(View view)
{
  Animation animation = Animation::New();

  view.Animate(animation)
    .Opacity(0.4f, 300_ms, AlphaFunction::EASE_OUT)
    .PositionY(48.0f, 300_ms, AlphaFunction::EASE_OUT);

  animation.Play();
}
```

Use `Dali::Ui::View::NewAnimationSpec()` when you want to build a reusable animation specification and apply it to one or more views.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

using namespace Dali;
using namespace Dali::Ui;

class ViewAnimator
{
public:
  ViewAnimator()
  : mShowSpec(View::NewAnimationSpec()
      .Opacity(1.0f, 250_ms, AlphaFunction::EASE_IN_OUT)
      .ScaleX(1.0f, 250_ms, AlphaFunction::EASE_IN_OUT)
      .ScaleY(1.0f, 250_ms, AlphaFunction::EASE_IN_OUT))
  {
  }

  void PlayShow(View view)
  {
    Animation animation = Animation::New();
    mShowSpec.ApplyTo(animation, view);
    animation.Play();
  }

private:
  ViewAnimationSpec mShowSpec;
};
```

The dali-ui animation API also supports view-owned visual properties such as background color, corner radius, corner squareness, borderline width, borderline color, and borderline offset.

```cpp
void Highlight(View view)
{
  Animation animation = Animation::New();

  view.Animate(animation)
    .BackgroundColor(UiColor(0x3366FF), 200_ms)
    .CornerRadius(Vector4(12.0f, 12.0f, 12.0f, 12.0f), 200_ms)
    .BorderlineWidth(2.0f, 200_ms);

  animation.Play();
}
```

Inherited transform-style animation targets use DALi property ownership. For example, opacity is identified by `Dali::Actor::Property::OPACITY`, position by `Dali::Actor::Property::POSITION`, and scale by `Dali::Actor::Property::SCALE`, while view-owned properties are identified by `Dali::Ui::View::Property`.

## Using View Property Identifiers

Most application code should prefer typed dali-ui methods and traits. Property identifiers are still useful when integrating with generic property-based systems, automation, tooling, or accessibility metadata.

Use `Dali::Ui::View::Property` for view-owned properties such as accessibility metadata, background, border, corners, focus links, layout mode, margin, padding, requested size, shadow, and offscreen rendering.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/dali-ui-foundation.h>

using namespace Dali;
using namespace Dali::Ui;

struct ViewPropertyIds
{
  Property::Index background;
  Property::Index borderlineWidth;
  Property::Index cornerRadius;
  Property::Index accessibilityName;
  Property::Index automationId;
};

ViewPropertyIds GetCommonViewPropertyIds()
{
  ViewPropertyIds ids;
  ids.background = View::Property::BACKGROUND;
  ids.borderlineWidth = View::Property::BORDERLINE_WIDTH;
  ids.cornerRadius = View::Property::CORNER_RADIUS;
  ids.accessibilityName = View::Property::ACCESSIBILITY_NAME;
  ids.automationId = View::Property::AUTOMATION_ID;
  return ids;
}
```

Use the property owner that matches the property. `Dali::Ui::View::Property::BACKGROUND`, `Dali::Ui::View::Property::BORDERLINE_COLOR`, `Dali::Ui::View::Property::CORNER_RADIUS`, `Dali::Ui::View::Property::MARGIN`, and `Dali::Ui::View::Property::REQUESTED_WIDTH` are view properties. `Dali::Actor::Property::OPACITY`, `Dali::Actor::Property::POSITION`, and `Dali::Actor::Property::SCALE` are inherited DALi actor properties used by view animation patterns.

```cpp
Property::Index ViewBackgroundProperty()
{
  return Dali::Ui::View::Property::BACKGROUND;
}

Property::Index ViewAccessibilityNameProperty()
{
  return Dali::Ui::View::Property::ACCESSIBILITY_NAME;
}

Property::Index AnimatedOpacityProperty()
{
  return Dali::Actor::Property::OPACITY;
}
```
